== Introduction
This book is thin. If you believe a book can only be good when it is gigantic, this is not for you. Thanks for reading this book, but you can stop now. If on the other hand, you like that I am telling you, this book is thin, that it only contains the stuff that should and need to be said and nothing more, then this book is for you. 

As such, this book won't tell you what Software-as-a-Service is — you should know that already. It won't tell you how to structure, design or build this nor the business around it. It won't tell you anything about markets or people in these. Because you like your time not to be wasted with too many words, unrelated stories and anecdotes. You just want the no-bullshit cut-to-the-chase information.

Welcome to the book, that's gonna teach you all you need and want to know about SaaS-App-Pricing. This book is going to explain to you how to determine the right price and pricing schema for your Software-as-a-Service (Web-)Application. And though many of the rules might also apply to things like Kickstarter Campaigns, this book focuses on reoccurring subscription pricing of SaaS for consumer and B2B-business.

If you are here to just get a number, let me tell you it is €29.95 per month (respective $39.95). This book is going to tell you why and which cases it is different. But if you don't care and just want a number, odds are, this is the number you want.


== What makes SaaS different?
Software as a Service business is a very interesting model. As it is in most of the case a subscription based system, you are not forced to sell to new customers but can focus on building a great product for your existing customers.

Another highly fascinating thing about SaaS Apps is, that they are essentially no costs. Of course, you need people to build it, make it better and scale it, but that is cheap in comparison to what costs you have in other businesses, where you need to buy expensive special vehicles, materials or tools. As the term says it, you are in the service business and a highly and cost-efficient scaling one, too.

And as software is your service, sure you have a certain set of features but every software is unique at the end of the day and you can't (and most people won't) compare the list of features from one App to the other. Most likely you have a feature no other competitor offers while they have features, you don't need or want to have. Which makes your customers, your customers and you always want to convince them with a different argument than "being cheaper" – your competitors, too, by the way.

Running a software in this business means, you are not bound to competitive pricing or have any numbers running the business for you. Setting the price for a software as a service offer is a total psychology game. But one of high importance as it is a key factor whether people can and want to buy (or effort) it. The beauty of it though, once you've find your target, it's gonna sell like hot cakes. And on top, you have basically no costs with upselling either. We'll come back to that a little later.

== Basic Principles of Pricing psychology

Software as a service product have a few spins to it, a few I've just mentioned before. Another one that comes with it, it the ability to repackage it into any kind of size for basically no extra costs. You can sell the same thing just in three or four different sizes. Thus allowing you to have an offer for each budget size.

And there we've already found one key instrument: have multiple tiers. To give the options and let the customer think about what they want. But be careful to give only a few. Giving too many options because a lot to read, compare and in the end too hard to decide – a fundamental problem with crowd funding pricing. These tiers should be viewable in one page, their differences and benefits clearly distinguishable. I have the best experiences with setting three pricing levels - some argue it's five, but I often feel that is too much to read (as you need five clear differentiations).

As said, pricing an SaaS is mostly psychology and the counter part is the customer.   

=== How low can you go?

The lowest of the tiers is the one, you can use for advertising and marketing. Try to make it as low as you can think without having the feeling of selling out to cheap. This is also the (only) tier you offer the free trial on. By making it rather cheap, this has the nice additional benefit that even if people the decide to not stick with you, if the number is low, they are less likely to cancel it (as it feels it's not worth the effort). So, if you can reasonably offer your service for €9.99/month, do that.

=== Too thin

Because it is too thin anyways. The offer of that lowest pricing shouldn't be bad or cheesy, but don't forget it is your marketing-offer to get people to look into your service. Offer a service,which is "just not quiet enough". You should have an idea about, who your customer is, done some personas and research, so you know what they need. Maybe they'll run through ten clients a month, then eight are included in your tier, they are running a radio stream with music so they need 192kb/s mp3, include up to 128kb, if they have revenue of 15k per month, your tier allows up to 10k – you get the picture.

The more obvious it is this tier isn't quiet enough for them, the better, don't let scream into their face, but use terms and numbers they understand. The reason you want to do that is the following: they are checking your pricing. Which means, they are interested in your service and most likely want to use it. If they just want to try it, those numbers don't mean much and they'll hit the "free trial button" without looking into it for too long. But if they really consider, then you've already sold it, you just need to settle on the price now. By making the cheapest unusable to them, they immediately move to the second tier.

=== The second is good, the third is to settle

Now this tier offers much more than the first one we've talked about. Not only can they run their business with it but it is almost too generous, offers much more than they ever feel to be needing. For just about double the initial price (or slightly less) - very good. And that is the price range they want to and _should settle_. But by offering so much already, all they ever wanted, they become curious about what more you could be offering. And they look at the third and compare it to the second.

Now here it becomes interesting. By increasing the price slightly but adding something extra-ordinary - even if they don't necessarily need it - they become very interested. Because there is so much more in there in comparison to what is in tier 2 but it isn't that much more expensive. So in comparison it even feels like a really good offer, you get more for your money. In my experience this is done the best by adding exactly one key thing on top. Like for the audio-stream example, add a second stream - it adds a lot but got "thrown in" rather cheap.

