=== Real world case

I did exactly this pricing range for a crowd funding campaign for a Hollywood movie and though it never finished (because of internal problems), we had it in the phase of money raising. I told them to put up the following tiers:

 * 9.95 € - you were thanked on the website, got access to the bonus material and live updates through the websites about the shoot, as well as a download-link for movie as soon as it gets released on Bluray

 * 29.95 € - Same as before, but you'd also be mentioned in the credits of the movie.

 * 49.95 € - Aside from the news updates, being mentioned in the credits, you'd also be receiving a real disc version of the Bluray.

This allowed the studio to advertise with "support this movie starting from 9.95€". But the real deal was, getting mentioned in the movie, so people were immediately checking the second higher tier as the first didn't offer this. And though many settled on this, for less than double the price, you'd also receive a Bluray - well, doesn't that sound great?

So, thought 57% of the people (another 21% went for the first and 22% for the second). We sold them a Bluray disc for 20€. A movie - not a DVD-set. A movie they already have access through a download link to. A Bluray discs, which costs essentially nothing in product (why they wanted to offer it as part of the lowest pricing range initially). We wouldn't have gotten anyone to pay for this, if I had said it this way. But through this pricing schema, we could. And they were happy to do so.

