=== Ending with the Nine

I've very bluntly ignored the discussing of the pricing numbers and given you cases that all end with the number 9. If you are at least a little familiar with the subject, you should be very aware that we don't exactly know why, but having the price end with a nine outsells every other option (with 5 and 7 right behind but off by far). This has been shown in a series of studies, like link:http://link.springer.com/article/10.1023%2FA%3A1023581927405[this one from MIT] and discussed in detail in books like link:http://www.amazon.com/dp/080909469X/ref=cm_sw_su_dp["Priceless" by William Poundstone] footnote:[Published at Hill and Wang, 2011, ISBN 978-0809094691] so I won't get into detail on this again.

=== Enterprise ain't part of this
This all only applies, if your customers are mainly end-consumers and small- and mid-size companies but not for enterprise. The basic rule goes like this: if the company is big enough to have someone, who's job is it to mainly buy this kinda stuff, they'll call you up and ask to negotiate a custom pricing tier with you. And even if that is only to justify the existence of their job (as they have work to do: negotiate with you), they'll do it.

But as this costs extra effort on your side in comparison to auto-serviced customers, don't forget to charge them for it, too. Aside from your three tiers, you add another box on the bottom saying you are open to discuss further models and individual pricing for bigger customers or special areas (like non-profits or education, like Google is doing). And that negotiation you go from 2 simultaneous stream to 10 and add a big support package on top, that you sell for at least ten times the highest price you have on your tiers. That at least puts it back into the price-range that enterprise is used to and happy talk about: they really rather buy the service for 5k€ than for 50€ as the later is harder to justify.

That is also why even your highest priced tier should have some limits you can sell to enterprise and high-class customers - otherwise you'd nothing to sell them. And even if they eventually settle for eight times the highest tier so they feel they negotiated stuff out of you, it was worth the effort for you. But don't ever think that this is an option to include via one-click sign-up. Enterprise won't do one-click-sign-up of it anyways.

== Upselling without Upsetting

I talked about the beauty of upselling within SaaS-Product before a little. The greatest thing is, that what you are upsellings usually doesn't cost you any more. And though a good pricing strategy on the overview page we've discussed before, can already get the people into getting the more expensive tier, there is more you can upsell with. Sadly, upselling has been abused by quite a few (like airlines tricking you into getting a "travel insurance" by already checking the field for you) and has a bad taste to it now, can even be upsetting to customers. Which is really not the first impression you want to leave starting business with them.

One company that gets upselling very right is Apple. And again it a question of the communication and way to present it to the other party, that decides whether it works or not. And though this is end-consumer hardware, the same principles still apply to Upselling of SaaS product during the initial checkout. So, let's see how they do it.

=== Case Study: Upselling like Apple
When you go to the Apple online store to buy a new MacBook Air (as an example), you are presented with different models, similar to our packages or tiers from before:

.Selecting a Macbook Air
image::image/page-1-above-fold.png[A Screenshot of the Macbook Air Selection]


Same as we discussed for our tiers, there are just a few things different in these tiers, that make for a big distinction: the first being the Screen size (either 11 inch or 13) and the secondary being the flash storage. By presenting those very blunt, Apple makes the question which one to buy not about the price but first about the screen size — which they do very clever by having the second screen even be presented bigger — and in the secondary stage about the storage. First you pick the screen size, then the storage and then you are presented with the price. The price in this way is merely a result of our decisions and wasn't part of the decision in the first place. 

And now that you've decided what you want, you don't really care that Apple is selling you 128GB of storage for 200EUR extra anymore. But it gets even better once you are selecting this one. Because then Apple presents you with the "configuration page", a second page to actually upsell you even more.

.The "configuration" page
image::image/apple-store-page-2.png[The configuration screen]

Sure, you can actually configure the CPU, memory and keyboard in here (which you probably want to do actually) but there is plenty of things listed, which are actually about selling you more things: how is an external screen, an AppleTV or a Printer part of a MacBook Air configuration? Well, it isn't.

But by having this second "configuration"-screen, Apple does something very smart here. It took the decision of which general package you picked out of the scope. That has already been decided, the other options aren't presented anymore. And by splitting this into two pages, you don't have to bother about comparing prices of the configuration to other packages anymore. Adding 8GB of RAM on a 13-inch could potentially cost more than on the 11-inch (which could even have plausible, technical reasons), but no costumer would actually go back and check. Because picking another basic package isn't of any question anymore.

Another thing you've hopefully noticed is the way this is presented: Apple takes four-fifth of the width to focus on the configuration. The summary of what you've selected on the other hand is just a tiny part on the right. And though it is showing the total price, always stays with the user and as such gives them total transparency about their choices, by keeping it to the top right, we are less likely to look at it or at least not until we've scrolled down the main part totally already.

By also splitting them into big chunks that basically cover the bigger part of your screen while you scroll over them, each upgrade becomes separate from the others, making them appear as individual, not too expensive choices. And I have to actively decide on each one, that I don't want them though it is only 29,99€. And by keeping them separate, the decision I just made for the thunderbolt cable has nothing to do with the mini-display-port-cable I am looking at right now. Look it's only 29,99€. In the customers brain the other decision has been done and labeled as such, so just because I want the mini-display-port, the customer would probably not go back and change his mind on items before in the list.

.Default is "None"
[NOTE]
====
One major flaw that many (airlines) do, is pre-selecting upsell-options for you and the user has to actively remove the selection often in a complicated way. Cheating a customer into upselling through this, is an obvious way to have more people upsell but makes the customer angry and once he figured it out, he doesn't want to listen anymore.

Unlike how Apple is doing it here, making it clear you don't get cheated into anything you don't want, it is your choice and we are happy either way, but we think this might be of interest for you, too. And the customer listens. And they buy. And they are happy about it. It is kind of sad that this actually needs to be stated ...
====

==== The upsell

Let's take a look at the individual things Apple tries to sell here. The same as on a normal product page, it needs to be selling the user, so it looks good, is interesting and gets quite some space. By giving upselling so much room, Apple has enough space to present the product and all important information and list the options. Just scrolling over them is going to take a little and at least one is going to catch your eye.

And once again, how they present it, is of high importance. Let's take this external storage as an example:

.Upselling you the Thunderbold storage
image::image/page-2-storage-none.png[Thunderbold Storage]

Not only does it have quite some room and scrolling over it takes long enough for our eye to catch and the brain to notice the content, but also the way of decision making is again like before. By presenting the price in square brackets it appears to be merely a consequence of the decision but not really part of it. No, the details of option to select are in foreground. And it gets better, because Apple isn't done upselling once you selected one option:

.After selecting an option, the price disappears
image::image/page-2-storage-selected.png[Selected a Storage]

Did you notice the difference? Apple changed the prices. As I have decided on an Option, not only does it become part of my decision (and the summary) so the price disappears, also the other prices are updated to only show the difference in pricing. Genius. Not only because now the more expensive options don't appear to be as expensive any more but also because by phrasing it "Substract 349,95€", even the "None" option now appears to be costing something triggered by providing a positive number. Our brain immediately notices that as high, and it takes a while before it processed that "substract" needs we have to negate it. 

And though thinking of the negative is something our brain generally can't do, by using words here this also requires other parts of the brain to process it. It would be quite different if instead of subtract it would show the minus sign or – even worse – color-code the values (red and green), things our brain would understand immediately.

But 

How apple designed their upselling process and why it is genius:

   - Second page
   - default off 
   - big space to convince about the upgrade
   - move price out of scope
   - focus on the cheap, individual upgrade
   - ignore other upgrades/there is no reason to have them comparable

