== Other pricing still makes sense:
That all said, I think there is good reason to price your SaaS-Service around the given tiers. But that doesn't mean you have to or should be doing this. As these pricings work and are most likely working for the majority of SaaS-Projects out there, there are still a few markets, where a different pricing (in terms of the actual numbers) makes much more sense.

=== Enterprise
I mentioned enterprise before: if the majority of your customers will be in that segment and you'd actually have to sell via the phone, the pricing categories don't make much sense because customer acquisition is not going through the Internet and self-signup and be way more expensive. Also, as said before, they like to talk about bigger numbers generally. Calling a head of sales to sell them a subscription of 50€/month just sounds like a waste of time to them.

=== High-priced customers
Another classic case I encountered at an incubator I mentored in Palestine, where one startup wanted to build a case-management-SaaS-Software for Arab Lawyers and wanted to price it at around 30$. I argued that Lawyers are a high-pricing audience, they don't buy suites because the price is low but because the price is high. They are used get paid a lot but also to pay a lot,their whole value-chain is high-priced from their suits, over the consultants they hire up to the parties they throw. The predominantly mentality in their line of business is that a product sold at that price can't be of high value. They'd rather be bragging how expensive something was than how cheap it was.

So in such a case I'd look at my target group and look for "what they'd be saving" and arrange my pricing around that. In this example, if the software is done properly, this would save the lawyer their office assistant - which would probably be costing them at around 600$ in the market we are talking about. So if you can offer the same service for 399$, argue that they'll still be saving a lot of money, it comes of as comparably cheap (compared to the office assistant) but still have them value the product a lot.

This is a very classic selling but also price-setting argument actually: finding a real world costs it would replace and put your tier lower than that but providing a similar service. This also directly puts you in pricing competition against something, which price most likely rather stable and won't undermine the costs of the technology very soon.

Other markets with a similar attitude would be doctors, recruiters, head-hunters and HR. And I am sure there are others, so look at your market and the customers closely. 

NOTE: Also, in this case the argument was rather simple for that price because at 30$ even if they got 10% of all Arab lawyers to sign up, they wouldn't get enough revenue to pay their own employees. So don't forget to also take that into account, when talking about the price you can offer.

=== Luxary and Brand
Another classic case of when you should avoid the how-low-can-you-go-rule is in luxury products and brand-associated services. It is a known phenomenon that if you decrease pricing for luxury products, you make less money. There always need to be the luxury gap between the ordinary champagne were the pricing ends around 70€ per bottle and the one luxury segment that starts at 600€. But making pricing your bottle at 500€, you are to expensive for the normal market but too cheap for the luxury segment. Luxury people buy because the price is intentionally too high.

A similar effect goes for brand-associated products and services - unless of course the brand focuses on being cheap generally. Normally brands try to create an emotional connection and become part of who you are. That also puts it in a certain pricing segment, that the customer defines itself in. By going under that segment, you might reach new customers, but you won't convince your usual segment. And that'd disrupt your market share in ways, you don't want to cope with. A good example for this would be offering a Cloud-Solution by Apple: the apple customer defines themselves as someone, who cares more about User experience and Design than money. But offering a market competitive pricing or even something cheaper, you risk of creating the feeling of doing something cheap. And you want to avoid that by all means.

